  <prompt>
    Wire `@spaarke/auth` v2 bootstrap into the EmailComposer Code Page per ADR-028 and the `spaarke-sso-binding` pattern. The Code Page is the ONLY Spaarke surface that imports `@spaarke/auth` directly — every shared library component (including the `<SendEmailPage />` wrapper this Code Page will host) receives `authenticatedFetch` via props, NOT by importing `@spaarke/auth` itself.

    Goal: After this task, the Code Page bootstraps SSO silently (no popup in steady state), produces a configured `authenticatedFetch` from auth context, and exposes it to the App tree via React context so task 033 can pass it into the `<SendEmailPage />` wrapper props.

    Mirror the auth bootstrap of `src/client/code-pages/DocumentRelationshipViewer/src/services/auth/MsalAuthProvider.ts` + `msalConfig.ts` + `authInit.ts` — same pattern, same library, same configuration shape.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Spaarke frontend + auth engineer. Authoritative on Spaarke Auth v2 architecture (ADR-028) and the canonical Code Page bootstrap (DocumentRelationshipViewer + LegalWorkspace patterns).
  </role>

  <goal>
    EmailComposer Code Page bootstraps `@spaarke/auth` v2 successfully:
    1. Silent token acquisition on cold load (no popup unless interactive consent required)
    2. `authenticatedFetch` available via React context inside App tree
    3. Configuration shape mirrors DocumentRelationshipViewer (same scopes, same authority, same redirect URI handling)
    4. NO direct `@spaarke/auth` import from any `@spaarke/ui-components` code reachable from the Code Page (binding rule per NFR-02)
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      Per spec NFR-02 + ADR-028, shared library components MUST NOT import `@spaarke/auth` directly. The Code Page bootstraps it, derives `authenticatedFetch`, and injects via props. This is the same pattern DocumentRelationshipViewer follows.

      The Code Page must work in two contexts: (a) direct URL navigation (e.g., user types `https://{org}/api/data/v9.2/WebResourceSet(...)?data=...`), and (b) launched via `Xrm.Navigation.navigateTo`. In both contexts the `@spaarke/auth` v2 silent-bootstrap should succeed without a popup; popup only appears on first-ever consent grant.
    </background>
    <relevant-files>
      <file>src/client/code-pages/EmailComposer/src/App.tsx (UPDATED — wrap with auth provider)</file>
      <file>src/client/code-pages/EmailComposer/src/auth/ or src/services/auth/ (UPDATED — copy + adapt from exemplar)</file>
      <file>src/client/code-pages/EmailComposer/src/index.tsx (potentially UPDATED — bootstrap call sequence)</file>
      <file>src/client/code-pages/EmailComposer/package.json (UPDATED — add @spaarke/auth dep if not present)</file>
      <file>src/client/code-pages/DocumentRelationshipViewer/src/services/auth/MsalAuthProvider.ts (EXEMPLAR)</file>
      <file>src/client/code-pages/DocumentRelationshipViewer/src/services/auth/msalConfig.ts (EXEMPLAR)</file>
      <file>src/client/code-pages/DocumentRelationshipViewer/src/services/authInit.ts (EXEMPLAR)</file>
    </relevant-files>
  </context>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="ADR-028">Code Page uses `@spaarke/auth` v2 bootstrap; no self-bootstrapped MSAL</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-028">Silent acquisition is the steady-state path; popup is exception (first-ever consent)</constraint>
    <constraint source="NFR-02">Shared library components MUST inject `authenticatedFetch` via props — NEVER import `@spaarke/auth`</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">Mirror DocumentRelationshipViewer auth bootstrap exactly (scope set, authority, cache, redirect URI) — do NOT introduce variants</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">Expose `authenticatedFetch` via React context so task 033 can wire it into the wrapper props</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">No `.claude/` writes in this Wave 2 task</constraint>
  </constraints>

