  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">`@spaarke/auth` is the only auth library imported; no `@azure/msal-browser` direct usage.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Silent token acquisition succeeds on cold load (no popup in steady state).</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`authenticatedFetch` is exposed via React Context and reachable from `<App />` children.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`code-review` skill returns no Critical findings on the auth files.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`adr-check` against ADR-028 + NFR-02 passes.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`npm run build` clean; no TypeScript errors.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">No `@spaarke/auth` import from any `@spaarke/ui-components` file (verify via grep; pre-existing rule).</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">No `.claude/` files modified in this task.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    The DocumentRelationshipViewer exemplar may name files differently (e.g., `MsalAuthProvider.ts` vs `AuthProvider.tsx`). Mirror whatever the exemplar uses to minimize variance — the goal is bit-for-bit similarity in auth bootstrap shape.

    The `<SendEmailPage />` wrapper from Wave 1 (task 023) consumes `authenticatedFetch` as a prop. Task 033 will wire `useContext(AuthContext).authenticatedFetch` into the wrapper's prop API.

    UQ from spec: NFR-02 binding rule is empirically verified — `@spaarke/ui-components/src/services/communicationApi.ts:21-23` documents the decoupling. This task reinforces by NOT importing `@spaarke/auth` anywhere in the shared lib.
  </notes>

